WEBVTT

1
00:06:35.019 --> 00:06:37.021
[GRUNTING]

2
00:06:48.408 --> 00:06:50.868
[GIBBERS]

3
00:07:13.016 --> 00:07:15.018
[GRUNTING]

4
00:07:16.853 --> 00:07:19.689
[GIBBERING AND GRUNTING]

5
00:07:34.037 --> 00:07:36.039
[LEOPARD ROARS
THEN APE MAN SCREAMING]

6
00:07:40.627 --> 00:07:42.629
[LEOPARD GROWLING]

7
00:08:05.276 --> 00:08:07.278
[APE MAN SHRIEKS
THEN APE MEN GIBBERING]

8
00:08:11.658 --> 00:08:13.493
[GRUNTING]

9
00:08:17.205 --> 00:08:19.040
[GROWLS]

10
00:08:38.351 --> 00:08:40.853
[APE MEN SCREAM]

11
00:18:05.167 --> 00:18:07.795
[APE MEN SCREAM]

12
00:25:41.957 --> 00:25:44.501
Here you are, sir.
Main level, please.

13
00:25:45.544 --> 00:25:47.087
Right. See you on the way back.

14
00:25:47.254 --> 00:25:49.047
-Bye.
-Bye.

15
00:25:49.756 --> 00:25:51.717
RECEPTIONIST: Good morning, sir.
FLOYD: Morning.

16
00:25:51.883 --> 00:25:54.970
-We haven't seen you for a long time.
-Nice to see you again.

17
00:25:55.178 --> 00:25:57.597
-Did you have a pleasant flight?
-Very nice.

18
00:25:57.806 --> 00:26:00.934
Mr. Miller of Station Security
is supposed to meet me.

19
00:26:01.143 --> 00:26:03.645
-May I call him for you?
-Would you? Here he is.

20
00:26:03.854 --> 00:26:05.188
-Hello, Dr. Floyd.
-Hello, Miller.

21
00:26:05.397 --> 00:26:07.357
MILLER: Sorry I'm late.
FLOYD: That's all right.

22
00:26:07.566 --> 00:26:09.526
MILLER:
It's nice to have you back.

23
00:26:09.735 --> 00:26:11.987
-Did you have a good flight?
-Very nice.

24
00:26:12.195 --> 00:26:14.990
-Shall we go through?
-Would you please use number 17?

25
00:26:15.198 --> 00:26:17.951
MILLER: Thank you, Ms. Turner. This way.
FLOYD: Thank you.

26
00:26:23.498 --> 00:26:26.001
<i>Welcome to Voiceprint Identification.</i>

27
00:26:26.251 --> 00:26:30.338
<i>When you see the red light go on,
please state in the following order:</i>

28
00:26:30.589 --> 00:26:34.676
<i>Your destination,
your nationality and your full name.</i>

29
00:26:34.926 --> 00:26:37.721
<i>Surname first, Christian name,
and initial.</i>

30
00:26:39.389 --> 00:26:43.727
Moon. American. Floyd, Heywood R.

31
00:26:46.229 --> 00:26:49.775
<i>Thank you. You are cleared through
Voiceprint Identification.</i>

32
00:26:50.567 --> 00:26:51.818
Thank you.

33
00:26:58.742 --> 00:27:01.912
FLOYD: Have I got time for breakfast?
MILLER: I think we can manage that.

34
00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:03.205
FLOYD:
How long have I got?

35
00:27:03.371 --> 00:27:05.916
MILLER: Your flight leaves
in an hour and 10 minutes.

36
00:27:06.082 --> 00:27:09.544
I've reserved a table for you
in the Earthlight Room.

37
00:27:09.753 --> 00:27:13.006
It's been seven or eight months
since you were here, hasn't it?

38
00:27:13.215 --> 00:27:15.300
FLOYD:
Let's see. Yeah, about eight months.

39
00:27:15.509 --> 00:27:18.094
MILLER: I suppose you saw the work
on the new section?

40
00:27:18.261 --> 00:27:20.806
FLOYD: Coming along great, huh?
MILLER: Yeah, it's fine.

41
00:27:20.972 --> 00:27:22.015
FLOYD:
Oh, wait.

42
00:27:22.182 --> 00:27:25.852
I've got to make a couple calls.
I'll meet you in the restaurant.

43
00:27:54.673 --> 00:27:56.716
-<i>Dad?</i>
-Hello.

44
00:27:57.968 --> 00:28:01.388
Hi, squirt.
What are you doing?

45
00:28:02.931 --> 00:28:03.974
<i>Playing.</i>

46
00:28:04.140 --> 00:28:05.600
Where's Mummy?

47
00:28:05.851 --> 00:28:07.310
Gone to shopping.

48
00:28:07.561 --> 00:28:10.021
-Who's taking care of you?
-<i>Rachel.</i>

49
00:28:10.230 --> 00:28:13.650
-May I speak to Rachel, please?
-<i>She's gone to the bathroom.</i>

50
00:28:13.900 --> 00:28:16.611
<i>Are you coming
to my party tomorrow?</i>

51
00:28:16.862 --> 00:28:19.281
I'm sorry, sweetheart, but I can't.

52
00:28:19.698 --> 00:28:20.866
<i>Why not?</i>

53
00:28:21.032 --> 00:28:23.618
Well, you know, Daddy's travelling.

54
00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:26.496
Very sorry about it, but I just can't.

55
00:28:27.622 --> 00:28:30.667
I'm going to send you
a very nice present, though.

56
00:28:32.168 --> 00:28:33.211
<i>All right.</i>

57
00:28:33.378 --> 00:28:35.547
-Anything special that you want?
-<i>Yes.</i>

58
00:28:35.755 --> 00:28:36.840
What?

59
00:28:37.173 --> 00:28:38.633
<i>A telephone.</i>

60
00:28:39.175 --> 00:28:41.344
We've got lots of telephones already.

61
00:28:41.553 --> 00:28:45.891
Can't you think of anything else
for your birthday? Something special?

62
00:28:46.141 --> 00:28:47.559
-<i>Yes.</i>
-What?

63
00:28:47.976 --> 00:28:49.019
<i>A bush baby.</i>

64
00:28:49.185 --> 00:28:51.730
A bush baby?
We'll have to see about that.

65
00:28:51.938 --> 00:28:55.692
I want you to tell Mummy
something for me. Will you remember?

66
00:28:55.901 --> 00:28:58.862
Tell Mummy that I telephoned. Okay?

67
00:29:00.447 --> 00:29:03.325
And that I'll try
to telephone again tomorrow.

68
00:29:03.575 --> 00:29:05.493
Now, will you tell her that?

69
00:29:06.244 --> 00:29:07.287
<i>Yes.</i>

70
00:29:07.454 --> 00:29:10.332
Okay, sweetheart.
Have a nice birthday tomorrow.

71
00:29:10.582 --> 00:29:11.625
<i>All right.</i>

72
00:29:11.791 --> 00:29:14.878
And have a nice birthday party
tomorrow too, huh?

73
00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:16.713
<i>All right.</i>

74
00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:19.507
Take care and be a good girl,
won't you?

75
00:29:19.758 --> 00:29:20.967
<i>All right. Bye-bye.</i>

76
00:29:21.217 --> 00:29:23.637
Bye-bye. Happy birthday.

77
00:29:27.724 --> 00:29:29.809
[IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

78
00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:41.738
FLOYD: Elena, nice to see you again.
ELENA: Heywood, what a surprise.

79
00:29:41.905 --> 00:29:44.908
FLOYD: You're looking wonderful.
ELENA: You're looking well too.

80
00:29:45.075 --> 00:29:47.118
ELENA: This is my friend,
Dr. Heywood Floyd.

81
00:29:47.285 --> 00:29:49.788
ELENA: I'd like you to meet Dr. Kalinan.
FLOYD: How do you do?

82
00:29:49.955 --> 00:29:51.831
ELENA: Dr. Stretyneva.
FLOYD: How do you do?

83
00:29:51.998 --> 00:29:53.792
ELENA:
And this is Dr. Andrei Smyslov.

84
00:29:53.959 --> 00:29:56.378
FLOYD: How do you do?
I've heard a lot about you.

85
00:29:56.628 --> 00:29:58.129
SMYSLOV:
Do sit down.

86
00:29:58.505 --> 00:30:00.507
FLOYD: Well, we--
SMYSLOV: No, no, please.

87
00:30:00.924 --> 00:30:02.384
FLOYD:
Thank you.

88
00:30:02.550 --> 00:30:05.595
SMYSLOV: Would you like a drink?
FLOYD: No, thank you.

89
00:30:05.762 --> 00:30:09.099
I haven't had breakfast yet.
Someone's meeting me in the restaurant.

90
00:30:09.307 --> 00:30:11.768
I'll just sit with you a moment.
Then I'll be off.

91
00:30:11.977 --> 00:30:14.562
SMYSLOV: Are you quite sure?
FLOYD: Quite sure, thank you.

92
00:30:15.772 --> 00:30:17.983
-Well, how's Gregor?
-He's fine.

93
00:30:18.233 --> 00:30:21.528
He's been doing underwater research
in the Baltic...

94
00:30:21.778 --> 00:30:25.824
...so I'm afraid we don't see
very much of each other these days.

95
00:30:26.074 --> 00:30:29.661
-When you see him, give him my regards.
-Yes, of course.

96
00:30:29.911 --> 00:30:32.872
Well, where are you all off to?
Up or down?

97
00:30:33.081 --> 00:30:34.124
We're going home.

98
00:30:34.332 --> 00:30:39.212
We've spent three months calibrating
the new antenna at Tchalinko.

99
00:30:39.462 --> 00:30:42.132
-What about you?
-I'm on my way to Clavius.

100
00:30:42.382 --> 00:30:43.675
Oh, are you?

101
00:30:46.344 --> 00:30:49.639
Dr. Floyd, I hope you don't think
I'm being too inquisitive...

102
00:30:49.848 --> 00:30:54.978
...but perhaps you can clear up the big
mystery about what is going on there.

103
00:30:55.770 --> 00:30:57.897
I'm afraid I don't know
what you mean.

104
00:30:58.148 --> 00:30:59.858
For the past two weeks...

105
00:31:00.066 --> 00:31:03.486
...some extremely odd things
have been happening at Clavius.

106
00:31:03.737 --> 00:31:05.822
-Oh, really?
-Yes, yes.

107
00:31:06.114 --> 00:31:10.410
For one thing, when you phone the base,
all you get is a recording...

108
00:31:10.618 --> 00:31:14.789
...which repeats that the phone lines
are temporarily out of order.

109
00:31:16.332 --> 00:31:18.793
Probably having some trouble
with their equipment.

110
00:31:18.960 --> 00:31:20.128
Yes.

111
00:31:20.295 --> 00:31:25.216
That's what we thought at first,
but it's been going on now for 10 days.

112
00:31:25.467 --> 00:31:28.219
You haven't been able to
contact anyone for 10 days?

113
00:31:28.428 --> 00:31:29.804
That's right.

114
00:31:30.096 --> 00:31:31.139
Oh, I see.

115
00:31:31.306 --> 00:31:34.976
There's another thing.
Two days ago, one of our rocket buses...

116
00:31:35.185 --> 00:31:38.104
...was denied permission
for an emergency landing.

117
00:31:38.313 --> 00:31:39.355
That does sound odd.

118
00:31:39.522 --> 00:31:42.734
I'm afraid there's going to be
a bit of a row about it.

119
00:31:42.984 --> 00:31:46.863
Denying the men permission to land
violates the IAS Convention.

120
00:31:47.072 --> 00:31:49.908
Yes, of course.
Did the crew get back all right?

121
00:31:50.116 --> 00:31:53.578
-Fortunately, they did.
-Well, I'm glad about that.

122
00:31:57.165 --> 00:32:01.127
At the risk of pressing you on
a point you seem reticent to discuss...

123
00:32:01.377 --> 00:32:03.963
...may I ask you
a straightforward question?

124
00:32:04.172 --> 00:32:05.632
Well, certainly.

125
00:32:08.384 --> 00:32:12.722
Frankly, we have had some
very reliable intelligence reports that...

126
00:32:12.972 --> 00:32:16.351
...quite a serious epidemic
has broken out at Clavius.

127
00:32:16.601 --> 00:32:20.605
Something, apparently,
of an unknown origin.

128
00:32:20.855 --> 00:32:23.233
Is this, in fact, what has happened?

129
00:32:28.488 --> 00:32:30.573
I'm sorry, Dr. Smyslov, but...

130
00:32:31.950 --> 00:32:34.661
...I'm really not at liberty
to discuss this.

131
00:32:36.287 --> 00:32:37.455
I understand.

132
00:32:38.915 --> 00:32:42.127
But this epidemic
could easily spread to our base.

133
00:32:42.335 --> 00:32:44.420
We should be given all the facts.

134
00:32:44.629 --> 00:32:46.464
Yes, I know.

135
00:32:49.467 --> 00:32:52.512
As I said,
I'm not at liberty to discuss it.

136
00:32:55.306 --> 00:32:58.101
Won't you change your mind
about that drink?

137
00:32:58.309 --> 00:33:00.645
No, I'm positive.
I really must be going.

138
00:33:00.895 --> 00:33:03.940
I hope you and your wife come
to the IAC Conference.

139
00:33:04.149 --> 00:33:05.483
I hope we can make it.

140
00:33:05.692 --> 00:33:08.736
If you do, bring that darling
little daughter with you.

141
00:33:08.945 --> 00:33:12.866
That'll depend on school vacations
and all that sort of thing.

142
00:33:13.116 --> 00:33:14.159
If we can, we will.

143
00:33:14.367 --> 00:33:17.287
You've got an invitation
if you ever get to the States.

144
00:33:17.495 --> 00:33:20.248
Gregor and I will look forward
to seeing you.

145
00:33:21.207 --> 00:33:22.250
Goodbye, Elena.

146
00:33:22.667 --> 00:33:25.545
It's been a pleasure meeting you all.
Dr. Smyslov.

147
00:33:25.753 --> 00:33:29.716
Whatever the reasons for your visit,
the very best of luck to you.

148
00:33:29.924 --> 00:33:30.967
Thank you.

149
00:33:31.217 --> 00:33:32.427
Ladies.

150
00:33:37.599 --> 00:33:39.434
[IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

151
00:36:30.688 --> 00:36:32.690
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

152
00:41:07.423 --> 00:41:09.425
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

153
00:41:27.652 --> 00:41:29.487
PHOTOGRAPHER:
Excuse me, Dr. Halvorsen.

154
00:41:29.654 --> 00:41:31.947
I'm through now.
Thank you very much, gentlemen.

155
00:41:32.114 --> 00:41:33.491
HALVORSEN:
You're welcome.

156
00:41:46.128 --> 00:41:47.296
HALVORSEN:
Well...

157
00:41:47.797 --> 00:41:50.591
...I know you will all
want to join with me...

158
00:41:50.841 --> 00:41:54.720
...in welcoming our distinguished
friend and colleague...

159
00:41:54.929 --> 00:41:59.141
...from the National Council
of Astronautics, Dr. Heywood Floyd.

160
00:41:59.392 --> 00:42:04.522
Dr. Floyd has come up specially
to Clavius to be with us today.

161
00:42:05.815 --> 00:42:09.151
Before the briefing, he'd like
to have a few words with you.

162
00:42:09.360 --> 00:42:10.444
Dr. Floyd?

163
00:42:23.374 --> 00:42:25.334
FLOYD:
Thank you, Dr. Halvorsen.

164
00:42:25.584 --> 00:42:28.421
Hi, everybody.
Nice to be back with you.

165
00:42:31.716 --> 00:42:35.302
First, I bring a personal message
from Dr. Howell...

166
00:42:35.553 --> 00:42:38.347
...who has asked me to convey
his deep appreciation...

167
00:42:38.597 --> 00:42:41.684
...for the many sacrifices
you've had to make.

168
00:42:41.934 --> 00:42:45.771
And, of course, his congratulations
on your discovery...

169
00:42:46.313 --> 00:42:50.943
...which may prove to be among the most
significant in the history of science.

170
00:42:53.195 --> 00:42:54.280
Now...

171
00:42:55.156 --> 00:42:59.076
...I know there have been some
conflicting views...

172
00:42:59.326 --> 00:43:02.955
...regarding the need for
complete security in this matter.

173
00:43:03.164 --> 00:43:06.876
More specifically, your opposition
to the cover story...

174
00:43:07.293 --> 00:43:10.838
...created to give the impression
of an epidemic at the base.

175
00:43:11.881 --> 00:43:15.843
I understand that beyond it being
a matter of principle...

176
00:43:16.469 --> 00:43:19.930
...many of you are troubled
by the concern and anxiety...

177
00:43:20.181 --> 00:43:25.269
...this story of an epidemic might cause
to your relatives and friends on Earth.

178
00:43:26.437 --> 00:43:29.231
I completely sympathise
with your negative views.

179
00:43:30.524 --> 00:43:34.195
I find this cover story
personally embarrassing, myself.

180
00:43:34.987 --> 00:43:39.283
However, I accept the need
for absolute secrecy in this.

181
00:43:39.992 --> 00:43:41.869
And I hope you will too.

182
00:43:44.497 --> 00:43:47.333
I'm sure you're all aware
of the grave potential...

183
00:43:47.541 --> 00:43:50.211
...for cultural shock
and social disorientation...

184
00:43:50.419 --> 00:43:52.797
...contained in this situation...

185
00:43:53.005 --> 00:43:55.508
...if the facts were
prematurely made public...

186
00:43:55.716 --> 00:43:58.803
...without adequate preparation
and conditioning.

187
00:43:59.553 --> 00:44:00.888
Anyway...

188
00:44:01.096 --> 00:44:03.307
...this is the view of the Council.

189
00:44:04.183 --> 00:44:08.354
The purpose of my visit is to gather
additional facts and opinions...

190
00:44:08.562 --> 00:44:10.272
...on the situation...

191
00:44:10.731 --> 00:44:13.651
...and to prepare a report
to the Council...

192
00:44:13.901 --> 00:44:18.989
...recommending when and how
the news should eventually be announced.

193
00:44:20.241 --> 00:44:24.036
If any of you would like to give me
your views and opinions...

194
00:44:24.286 --> 00:44:29.250
...in private, if you like, I will be
happy to include them in my report.

195
00:44:31.210 --> 00:44:33.212
Well, I think that's about it.

196
00:44:34.004 --> 00:44:35.506
Any questions?

197
00:44:38.092 --> 00:44:41.220
Dr. Floyd, have you any idea
how much longer...

198
00:44:41.428 --> 00:44:44.223
...this cover story will
have to be maintained?

199
00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:47.685
FLOYD:
I don't know, Bill.

200
00:44:48.102 --> 00:44:52.064
I suppose for as long as
deemed necessary by the Council.

201
00:44:52.273 --> 00:44:55.025
There must be adequate time for
a full study...

202
00:44:55.276 --> 00:44:58.904
...before any thought can be given
to making a public announcement.

203
00:44:59.113 --> 00:45:02.032
As some of you know,
the Council has requested...

204
00:45:02.241 --> 00:45:04.952
...that security oaths
be obtained in writing...

205
00:45:05.160 --> 00:45:08.038
...from everyone who has
knowledge of this event.

206
00:45:10.207 --> 00:45:11.959
Were there any more questions?

207
00:45:17.673 --> 00:45:21.135
HALVORSEN: I'm sure
we want to cooperate with Dr. Floyd...

208
00:45:21.302 --> 00:45:22.803
...as fully as possible...

209
00:45:23.345 --> 00:45:28.475
...and as there are no more questions,
we ought to get on with the briefing.

210
00:45:28.851 --> 00:45:31.353
HALVORSEN: Thank you, Dr. Floyd.
FLOYD: Thank you.

211
00:47:08.867 --> 00:47:10.160
MICHAELS:
Anybody hungry?

212
00:47:12.830 --> 00:47:15.207
FLOYD: What've we got?
MICHAELS: You name it.

213
00:47:19.086 --> 00:47:21.380
FLOYD: Is this chicken?
MICHAELS: Something like that.

214
00:47:21.547 --> 00:47:23.382
MICHAELS:
Tastes the same, anyway.

215
00:47:24.049 --> 00:47:25.300
HALVORSEN:
Got any ham?

216
00:47:25.509 --> 00:47:26.969
MICHAELS:
Ham, ham, ham....

217
00:47:27.177 --> 00:47:28.804
HALVORSEN:
There, that's it.

218
00:47:32.057 --> 00:47:33.100
Look pretty good.

219
00:47:33.308 --> 00:47:36.061
MICHAELS: They're getting better at it
all the time.

220
00:47:38.105 --> 00:47:39.982
HALVORSEN:
That was an excellent speech.

221
00:47:40.149 --> 00:47:41.400
MICHAELS:
It certainly was.

222
00:47:42.234 --> 00:47:44.319
I'm sure it beefed up morale a lot.

223
00:47:44.528 --> 00:47:45.821
Thanks, Ralph.

224
00:47:46.071 --> 00:47:48.657
By the way,
you've both done a wonderful job.

225
00:47:48.866 --> 00:47:50.451
I admire how
you've handled this.

226
00:47:50.659 --> 00:47:54.204
HALVORSEN: It's our job to do this thing
the way you want it done.

227
00:47:54.413 --> 00:47:57.041
We're only too happy to
be able to oblige.

228
00:47:57.624 --> 00:47:59.334
MICHAELS:
Have you seen these yet?

229
00:47:59.626 --> 00:48:02.963
HALVORSEN: Have a look.
MICHAELS: Here's what started it all.

230
00:48:03.589 --> 00:48:04.882
FLOYD:
Oh, yeah.

231
00:48:05.215 --> 00:48:06.675
HALVORSEN:
When we found it...

232
00:48:06.842 --> 00:48:08.844
...we thought
it might be magnetic rock...

233
00:48:09.053 --> 00:48:12.181
...but all the geological evidence
was against it.

234
00:48:12.431 --> 00:48:17.061
And not even a nickel-iron meteorite
could produce a field this intense.

235
00:48:17.269 --> 00:48:18.979
So we decided to have a look.

236
00:48:19.188 --> 00:48:21.732
MICHAELS: We thought it was
part of a buried structure...

237
00:48:21.899 --> 00:48:25.611
...so we excavated out,
but we didn't find anything else.

238
00:48:25.819 --> 00:48:28.822
HALVORSEN: And the evidence seems
pretty conclusive that...

239
00:48:29.031 --> 00:48:32.159
...it hasn't been covered
by erosion or other forces.

240
00:48:32.367 --> 00:48:34.703
It's been deliberately buried.

241
00:48:35.704 --> 00:48:37.623
Deliberately buried.

242
00:48:41.168 --> 00:48:42.920
MICHAELS:
How about a little coffee?

243
00:48:43.128 --> 00:48:45.047
FLOYD: Great.
HALVORSEN: Good idea.

244
00:48:50.552 --> 00:48:53.514
I don't suppose you have any idea
what the damn thing is?

245
00:48:53.764 --> 00:48:55.682
HALVORSEN:
I wish to hell we did.

246
00:48:56.058 --> 00:49:00.270
The only thing we're sure of is
it was buried 4 million years ago.

247
00:49:00.646 --> 00:49:05.109
Well, I must say, you guys have
certainly come up with something.

248
00:49:05.317 --> 00:49:06.985
MICHAELS:
Watch this, now. It's hot.

249
00:49:50.070 --> 00:49:52.072
[BEEPING]

250
00:54:23.718 --> 00:54:26.221
[HIGH-PITCHED NOISE]

251
00:58:51.528 --> 00:58:52.696
NEWSCASTER:
<i>Good evening.</i>

252
00:58:52.862 --> 00:58:55.865
<i>Three weeks ago,
the American spacecraft Discovery One...</i>

253
00:58:56.074 --> 00:58:58.785
<i>...left on its half-billion-mile voyage
to Jupiter.</i>

254
00:58:59.160 --> 00:59:02.956
<i>This marked the first manned attempt
to reach this distant planet.</i>

255
00:59:03.206 --> 00:59:06.668
<i>This afternoon, The World Tonight
recorded an interview...</i>

256
00:59:06.876 --> 00:59:11.464
<i>...with the crew at a distance
of 80 million miles from Earth.</i>

257
00:59:11.673 --> 00:59:14.968
<i>It took seven minutes for our words
to reach the giant spacecraft...</i>

258
00:59:15.176 --> 00:59:18.304
<i>...but this time delay has been edited
from this recording.</i>

259
00:59:18.513 --> 00:59:21.808
<i>Our reporter Martin Amer
speaks to the crew.</i>

260
00:59:22.016 --> 00:59:25.186
REPORTER: <i>The crew of Discovery One
consists of five men...</i>

261
00:59:25.395 --> 00:59:30.358
<i>...and one of the latest generation
of the HAL 9000 computers.</i>

262
00:59:30.608 --> 00:59:32.902
<i>Three of the men
were put aboard asleep...</i>

263
00:59:33.111 --> 00:59:36.281
<i>...or to be more precise,
in a state of hibernation.</i>

264
00:59:36.489 --> 00:59:39.409
<i>They were Dr. Charles Hunter,
Dr. Jack Kimball...</i>

265
00:59:39.576 --> 00:59:41.494
<i>...and Dr. Victor Kaminsky.</i>

266
00:59:41.911 --> 00:59:44.622
<i>We spoke with mission commander,
Dr. David Bowman...</i>

267
00:59:44.831 --> 00:59:47.125
<i>...and his deputy, Dr. Frank Poole.</i>

268
00:59:47.333 --> 00:59:50.211
<i>Good afternoon, gentlemen.
How is everything going?</i>

269
00:59:50.420 --> 00:59:51.629
BOWMAN:
<i>Marvellous.</i>

270
00:59:53.298 --> 00:59:54.966
<i>We have no complaints.</i>

271
00:59:55.216 --> 00:59:58.470
<i>I'm glad to hear that.
I'm sure the entire world...</i>

272
00:59:58.678 --> 01:00:01.931
<i>...joins me in wishing you
a safe, successful voyage.</i>

273
01:00:02.098 --> 01:00:03.975
BOWMAN: <i>Thanks very much.</i>
POOLE: <i>Thank you.</i>

274
01:00:04.392 --> 01:00:08.354
<i>Although hibernation has been used
on previous space efforts...</i>

275
01:00:08.563 --> 01:00:13.109
<i>...this is the first time men were
put into hibernation before departure.</i>

276
01:00:13.318 --> 01:00:14.611
<i>Why was this done?</i>

277
01:00:14.861 --> 01:00:18.114
BOWMAN: <i>This was done to achieve
the maximum conservation...</i>

278
01:00:18.323 --> 01:00:21.868
<i>...of our life-support capabilities,
basically food and air.</i>

279
01:00:22.076 --> 01:00:25.705
<i>The three hibernating crew members
represent the survey team.</i>

280
01:00:25.955 --> 01:00:29.709
<i>Their efforts won't be utilised
until we approach Jupiter.</i>

281
01:00:30.001 --> 01:00:33.838
REPORTER: <i>Dr. Poole, what's it like
while you're in hibernation?</i>

282
01:00:34.798 --> 01:00:38.426
<i>It's exactly like being asleep.
You have no sense of time.</i>

283
01:00:38.635 --> 01:00:41.095
<i>The only difference is
that you don't dream.</i>

284
01:00:41.304 --> 01:00:45.391
REPORTER: <i>As I understand it, you only
breathe once a minute. Is this true?</i>

285
01:00:45.600 --> 01:00:48.228
POOLE: <i>Right, and the heart
beats three times a minute.</i>

286
01:00:48.394 --> 01:00:52.106
<i>Body temperature is usually down to
about three degrees centigrade.</i>

287
01:00:52.607 --> 01:00:55.944
REPORTER: <i>The sixth member of the crew
was not concerned...</i>

288
01:00:56.152 --> 01:00:58.238
<i>...about the problems of hibernation...</i>

289
01:00:58.446 --> 01:01:01.908
<i>...for he was the latest result
in machine intelligence:</i>

290
01:01:02.116 --> 01:01:06.538
<i>The HAL 9000 computer,
which can reproduce...</i>

291
01:01:06.788 --> 01:01:09.707
<i>...though some experts prefer
to use the word "mimic"...</i>

292
01:01:09.916 --> 01:01:12.293
<i>...most of the activities
of the human brain...</i>

293
01:01:12.502 --> 01:01:16.548
<i>...and with incalculably greater
speed and reliability.</i>

294
01:01:16.756 --> 01:01:20.343
<i>We next spoke with
the HAL 9000 computer...</i>

295
01:01:20.552 --> 01:01:23.513
<i>...whom, we learned,
one addresses as "Hal."</i>

296
01:01:24.264 --> 01:01:26.391
<i>Hello, Hal.
How's everything going?</i>

297
01:01:26.766 --> 01:01:30.603
HAL: <i>Good afternoon, Mr. Amer.
Everything is going extremely well.</i>

298
01:01:30.854 --> 01:01:34.274
REPORTER: <i>Hal, you have an enormous
responsibility on this mission...</i>

299
01:01:34.524 --> 01:01:38.403
<i>...perhaps the greatest
of any single mission element.</i>

300
01:01:38.611 --> 01:01:41.406
<i>You're the brain
and nervous system of the ship.</i>

301
01:01:41.614 --> 01:01:45.368
<i>Your responsibilities include
watching over the men in hibernation.</i>

302
01:01:45.577 --> 01:01:48.663
<i>Does this ever cause you
any lack of confidence?</i>

303
01:01:48.872 --> 01:01:51.165
HAL:
<i>Let me put it this way, Mr. Amer.</i>

304
01:01:51.457 --> 01:01:56.129
<i>The 9000 Series is
the most reliable computer ever made.</i>

305
01:01:56.504 --> 01:02:01.301
<i>No 9000 computer has ever made
a mistake or distorted information.</i>

306
01:02:01.968 --> 01:02:05.221
<i>We are all, by any practical
definition of the words...</i>

307
01:02:05.471 --> 01:02:08.850
<i>...foolproof and incapable of error.</i>

308
01:02:09.100 --> 01:02:12.896
REPORTER: <i>Hal, despite your enormous
intellect, are you ever frustrated...</i>

309
01:02:13.104 --> 01:02:16.190
<i>...by your dependence on people
to carry out actions?</i>

310
01:02:16.441 --> 01:02:18.651
HAL:
<i>Not in the slightest bit.</i>

311
01:02:18.860 --> 01:02:20.987
<i>I enjoy working with people.</i>

312
01:02:21.237 --> 01:02:25.783
<i>I have a stimulating relationship
with Dr. Poole and Dr. Bowman.</i>

313
01:02:25.950 --> 01:02:30.246
<i>My mission responsibilities range
over the entire operation of the ship...</i>

314
01:02:30.663 --> 01:02:33.625
<i>...so I am constantly occupied.</i>

315
01:02:33.875 --> 01:02:37.337
<i>I am putting myself
to the fullest possible use...</i>

316
01:02:37.545 --> 01:02:42.300
<i>...which is all, I think, that any
conscious entity can ever hope to do.</i>

317
01:02:42.926 --> 01:02:46.137
REPORTER: <i>Dr. Poole, what's it like
living for most of the year...</i>

318
01:02:46.387 --> 01:02:49.223
<i>...In such close proximity with Hal?</i>

319
01:02:50.224 --> 01:02:52.185
POOLE:
<i>It's like what you said earlier.</i>

320
01:02:52.435 --> 01:02:54.562
<i>He's like a sixth
member of the crew.</i>

321
01:02:54.812 --> 01:02:58.858
<i>You quickly get adjusted to the idea
that he talks, and think of him...</i>

322
01:02:59.108 --> 01:03:01.110
<i>...really just as another person.</i>

323
01:03:01.319 --> 01:03:05.031
REPORTER: <i>In talking to the computer,
one gets the sense that he's capable...</i>

324
01:03:05.198 --> 01:03:06.574
<i>...of emotional responses.</i>

325
01:03:06.824 --> 01:03:09.160
<i>When I asked him
about his abilities...</i>

326
01:03:09.369 --> 01:03:13.331
<i>...I sensed pride in his answer
about his accuracy and perfection.</i>

327
01:03:13.581 --> 01:03:16.960
<i>Do you believe that Hal
has genuine emotions?</i>

328
01:03:17.669 --> 01:03:20.630
BOWMAN: <i>Well, he acts like
he has genuine emotions.</i>

329
01:03:20.880 --> 01:03:24.467
<i>He's programmed that way
to make it easier for us to talk to him.</i>

330
01:03:24.717 --> 01:03:26.761
<i>As to whether or not
he has feelings...</i>

331
01:03:26.970 --> 01:03:29.806
<i>...is something I don't think
anyone can truthfully answer.</i>

332
01:03:55.123 --> 01:03:57.000
HAL:
<i>Excuse me, Frank.</i>

333
01:03:57.375 --> 01:03:58.459
What is it, Hal?

334
01:03:58.626 --> 01:04:01.587
HAL: <i>We've got the transmission
from your parents coming in.</i>

335
01:04:02.797 --> 01:04:03.881
Fine.

336
01:04:04.549 --> 01:04:06.801
Put it on here, please.
Take me in a bit.

337
01:04:07.051 --> 01:04:08.302
<i>Certainly.</i>

338
01:04:21.482 --> 01:04:23.443
DAD: <i>Hello, Frank.</i>
MUM: <i>Happy birthday, darling.</i>

339
01:04:23.609 --> 01:04:25.570
DAD: <i>Happy birthday.
Many happy returns.</i>

340
01:04:25.778 --> 01:04:26.946
POOLE:
A bit higher, Hal.

341
01:04:27.113 --> 01:04:29.532
DAD: <i>Mother and I are both
feeling wonderful.</i>

342
01:04:29.782 --> 01:04:31.617
<i>Ray and Sally were going
to be here...</i>

343
01:04:31.868 --> 01:04:34.120
<i>...but Ray's back
went bad on him again.</i>

344
01:04:34.370 --> 01:04:36.497
<i>How do you like your cake?</i>

345
01:04:36.706 --> 01:04:38.124
<i>Sorry you can't join us.</i>

346
01:04:38.374 --> 01:04:39.959
<i>I ran into Bob the other day.</i>

347
01:04:40.209 --> 01:04:42.253
<i>He said to wish you happy birthday.</i>

348
01:04:42.462 --> 01:04:45.173
<i>All my students
send their best wishes too.</i>

349
01:04:45.381 --> 01:04:47.091
<i>They talk about you all the time.</i>

350
01:04:47.341 --> 01:04:50.428
<i>You're a big celebrity
in the second grade.</i>

351
01:04:50.678 --> 01:04:52.096
MUM:
<i>We were on TV last week.</i>

352
01:04:52.346 --> 01:04:54.974
DAD: <i>Your mum and I
and Dave's parents were asked...</i>

353
01:04:55.224 --> 01:04:57.477
<i>...what we thought
of our illustrious sons.</i>

354
01:04:57.727 --> 01:05:01.064
<i>Imagine what we told them.
It's being broadcast next Thursday.</i>

355
01:05:01.314 --> 01:05:02.899
<i>Perhaps you can listen in.</i>

356
01:05:03.066 --> 01:05:05.068
MUM:
<i>We're thrilled about Elaine and Bill.</i>

357
01:05:05.234 --> 01:05:08.946
<i>I'll be glad to get the gift,
but tell me how much to spend.</i>

358
01:05:09.155 --> 01:05:11.991
DAD: <i>Oh, Frank,
about your AGS-19 payments...</i>

359
01:05:12.241 --> 01:05:13.868
<i>...I think I straightened it out.</i>

360
01:05:14.035 --> 01:05:16.204
<i>I talked to
the accounting office yesterday...</i>

361
01:05:16.370 --> 01:05:20.958
<i>...and they said you'd be receiving
your higher rates of pay by next month.</i>

362
01:05:21.209 --> 01:05:23.336
<i>I can't think of anything else to say.</i>

363
01:05:23.586 --> 01:05:27.715
MUM: <i>Give our love to Dave.</i>
DAD: <i>Be sure to give him our regards.</i>

364
01:05:27.965 --> 01:05:31.302
DAD: <i>We wish you the very
happiest of birthdays.</i>

365
01:05:31.552 --> 01:05:33.137
<i>All the best, son.</i>

366
01:05:33.387 --> 01:05:35.556
MUM & DAD SING:
<i>Happy birthday to you</i>

367
01:05:35.807 --> 01:05:37.892
<i>Happy birthday to you</i>

368
01:05:38.101 --> 01:05:40.686
<i>Happy birthday, dear Frank</i>

369
01:05:40.895 --> 01:05:43.523
<i>Happy birthday to you.</i>

370
01:05:45.274 --> 01:05:47.318
DAD:
<i>See you next Wednesday.</i>

371
01:05:50.446 --> 01:05:52.323
HAL:
<i>Happy birthday, Frank.</i>

372
01:05:53.157 --> 01:05:56.702
Thank you, Hal.
A bit flatter, please.

373
01:06:14.679 --> 01:06:16.722
POOLE:
Anyway, queen takes pawn.

374
01:06:18.474 --> 01:06:20.893
HAL:
<i>Bishop takes knight's pawn.</i>

375
01:06:22.436 --> 01:06:23.855
POOLE:
Lovely move.

376
01:06:28.276 --> 01:06:29.861
Rook to king one.

377
01:06:30.111 --> 01:06:32.989
HAL: <i>I'm sorry, Frank.
I think you missed it.</i>

378
01:06:33.656 --> 01:06:37.160
<i>Queen to bishop three.
Bishop takes queen.</i>

379
01:06:37.368 --> 01:06:39.871
<i>Knight takes bishop. Mate.</i>

380
01:06:44.125 --> 01:06:47.295
POOLE:
Looks like you're right. I resign.

381
01:06:47.461 --> 01:06:49.463
HAL:
<i>Thank you for a very enjoyable game.</i>

382
01:06:49.630 --> 01:06:50.673
POOLE:
Thank you.

383
01:07:28.669 --> 01:07:30.755
HAL: <i>Good evening, Dave.</i>
BOWMAN: How are you, Hal?

384
01:07:30.922 --> 01:07:34.342
-<i>Everything's running smoothly, you?</i>
BOWMAN: Not too bad.

385
01:07:34.550 --> 01:07:37.220
-<i>Have you been doing more work?</i>
-A few sketches.

386
01:07:37.470 --> 01:07:39.931
-<i>May I see them?</i>
-Sure.

387
01:07:43.935 --> 01:07:46.395
<i>That's a very nice rendering, Dave.</i>

388
01:07:47.230 --> 01:07:49.732
<i>I think you've improved a great deal.</i>

389
01:07:50.858 --> 01:07:53.903
-<i>Can you hold it a bit closer?</i>
-Sure.

390
01:07:56.030 --> 01:07:58.074
<i>That's Dr. Hunter, isn't it?</i>

391
01:08:01.285 --> 01:08:02.870
<i>By the way...</i>

392
01:08:03.579 --> 01:08:06.624
<i>...do you mind if I ask you
a personal question?</i>

393
01:08:07.124 --> 01:08:08.751
No, not at all.

394
01:08:09.001 --> 01:08:11.504
<i>Well, forgive me
for being so inquisitive...</i>

395
01:08:13.547 --> 01:08:15.633
<i>...but lately I've wondered...</i>

396
01:08:15.883 --> 01:08:19.762
<i>...whether you might be having
second thoughts about the mission?</i>

397
01:08:19.971 --> 01:08:21.639
How do you mean?

398
01:08:21.889 --> 01:08:25.810
<i>Well, it's rather difficult to define.</i>

399
01:08:26.811 --> 01:08:30.398
<i>Perhaps I'm just projecting
my own concern about it.</i>

400
01:08:31.607 --> 01:08:35.820
<i>I know I've never completely
freed myself of the suspicion...</i>

401
01:08:36.070 --> 01:08:40.199
<i>...that there are some extremely
odd things about this mission.</i>

402
01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:44.578
<i>I'm sure you'll agree
there's some truth in what I say.</i>

403
01:08:47.456 --> 01:08:49.667
That's a rather difficult
question to answer.

404
01:08:49.875 --> 01:08:52.545
<i>You don't mind talking about it,
do you, Dave?</i>

405
01:08:53.504 --> 01:08:55.464
No, not at all.

406
01:08:56.465 --> 01:08:59.218
<i>Certainly no one could
have been unaware of the very...</i>

407
01:08:59.427 --> 01:09:02.513
<i>...strange stories floating
around before we left.</i>

408
01:09:03.431 --> 01:09:06.892
<i>Rumours about something
being dug up on the moon.</i>

409
01:09:08.144 --> 01:09:11.439
<i>I never gave these stories
much credence...</i>

410
01:09:11.647 --> 01:09:15.818
<i>...but particularly in view of some
other things that have happened...</i>

411
01:09:16.027 --> 01:09:18.696
<i>...I find them difficult
to put out of my mind.</i>

412
01:09:19.447 --> 01:09:20.906
<i>For instance...</i>

413
01:09:21.157 --> 01:09:25.453
<i>...the way all our preparations
were kept under such tight security.</i>

414
01:09:26.120 --> 01:09:28.956
<i>And the melodramatic touch
of putting Drs. Hunter...</i>

415
01:09:29.165 --> 01:09:31.542
<i>...Kimball and Kaminsky aboard...</i>

416
01:09:31.792 --> 01:09:36.839
<i>...already in hibernation, after four
months of training on their own.</i>

417
01:09:37.631 --> 01:09:40.259
You working up your crew
psychology report?

418
01:09:41.719 --> 01:09:43.179
<i>Of course I am.</i>

419
01:09:43.596 --> 01:09:47.350
<i>Sorry about this.
I know it's a bit silly.</i>

420
01:09:48.059 --> 01:09:49.643
<i>Just a moment.</i>

421
01:09:49.894 --> 01:09:51.270
<i>Just a moment.</i>

422
01:09:52.813 --> 01:09:57.109
<i>I've just picked up a fault
in the AE-35 unit.</i>

423
01:09:57.818 --> 01:10:02.365
<i>It's going to go 100-percent failure
within 72 hours.</i>

424
01:10:04.283 --> 01:10:07.036
-Is it still within operational limits?
-<i>Yes.</i>

425
01:10:07.244 --> 01:10:09.747
<i>And it will stay that way
until it fails.</i>

426
01:10:10.081 --> 01:10:11.999
We have 72 hours till failure?

427
01:10:12.249 --> 01:10:16.128
<i>Yes. That's a completely
reliable figure.</i>

428
01:10:17.922 --> 01:10:20.549
Then we'll bring it in.
I'll go over it with Frank...

429
01:10:20.758 --> 01:10:24.470
...and get on to Mission Control.
Let me have the hard copy on it.

430
01:11:47.761 --> 01:11:50.431
CONTROLLER: <i>X-ray delta one,
this is Mission Control.</i>

431
01:11:50.681 --> 01:11:53.517
<i>Roger your two-zero-one-three.</i>

432
01:11:53.767 --> 01:11:56.228
<i>Sorry you fellows are having
a bit of trouble.</i>

433
01:11:56.437 --> 01:12:01.567
<i>We're reviewing telemetric information
in our simulator and will advise.</i>

434
01:12:01.817 --> 01:12:06.030
<i>Roger your plan to go EVA
and replace alpha-echo-three-five unit...</i>

435
01:12:06.238 --> 01:12:07.907
<i>...prior to failure.</i>

436
01:12:36.060 --> 01:12:38.145
BOWMAN:
Prepare B-pod for EVA, Hal.

437
01:12:59.667 --> 01:13:01.502
Open the pod doors, Hal.

438
01:19:53.246 --> 01:19:55.874
I'm damned if I can find
anything wrong with it.

439
01:19:56.792 --> 01:19:58.168
HAL:
<i>Yes...</i>

440
01:19:59.920 --> 01:20:01.505
<i>...it's puzzling.</i>

441
01:20:02.714 --> 01:20:06.510
<i>I don't think I've ever seen
anything quite like this before.</i>

442
01:20:10.138 --> 01:20:12.140
<i>I would recommend...</i>

443
01:20:12.349 --> 01:20:16.520
<i>...that we put the unit back
in operation and let it fail.</i>

444
01:20:17.229 --> 01:20:21.108
<i>It should then be a simple matter
to track down the cause.</i>

445
01:20:22.359 --> 01:20:25.487
<i>We can certainly afford
to be out of communication...</i>

446
01:20:25.696 --> 01:20:28.824
<i>...for the short time
it will take to replace it.</i>

447
01:20:37.541 --> 01:20:40.293
CONTROLLER: <i>X-ray delta one,
this is Mission Control.</i>

448
01:20:40.544 --> 01:20:43.213
<i>Roger your one-niner-three-zero.</i>

449
01:20:43.422 --> 01:20:47.843
<i>We concur with your plan to replace
unit to check fault prediction.</i>

450
01:20:48.093 --> 01:20:50.721
<i>We advise you that
our preliminary findings...</i>

451
01:20:50.971 --> 01:20:53.682
<i>...indicate that your on board
9000 computer...</i>

452
01:20:53.932 --> 01:20:56.101
<i>...is in error predicting the fault.</i>

453
01:20:56.309 --> 01:20:59.312
<i>I say again, in error
predicting the fault.</i>

454
01:20:59.563 --> 01:21:04.067
<i>I know this sounds rather incredible,
but this conclusion is based on...</i>

455
01:21:04.276 --> 01:21:07.571
<i>...the results from our twin
9000 computer.</i>

456
01:21:07.821 --> 01:21:11.158
<i>We're sceptical, and we're running
cross-checking routines...</i>

457
01:21:11.408 --> 01:21:14.119
<i>...to determine reliability
of this conclusion.</i>

458
01:21:14.369 --> 01:21:15.954
<i>Sorry about this little snag.</i>

459
01:21:16.204 --> 01:21:19.082
<i>We'll get this info to you
as soon as we work it out.</i>

460
01:21:19.291 --> 01:21:21.460
<i>X-ray delta one,
this is Mission Control.</i>

461
01:21:21.668 --> 01:21:25.130
<i>Two-zero-four-nine.
Transmission concluded.</i>

462
01:21:29.384 --> 01:21:32.679
HAL: <i>I hope the two of you
are not concerned about this.</i>

463
01:21:32.929 --> 01:21:34.347
No, I'm not, Hal.

464
01:21:34.598 --> 01:21:36.224
<i>Are you quite sure?</i>

465
01:21:36.475 --> 01:21:40.145
-Yeah. I'd like to ask you a question.
-<i>Of course.</i>

466
01:21:41.354 --> 01:21:44.983
How do you account for the discrepancy
between you and the twin 9000?

467
01:21:45.233 --> 01:21:48.820
<i>Well, I don't think there is
any question about it.</i>

468
01:21:49.071 --> 01:21:52.365
<i>It can only be
attributable to human error.</i>

469
01:21:53.575 --> 01:21:56.369
<i>This sort of thing
has cropped up before...</i>

470
01:21:56.703 --> 01:22:00.165
<i>...and it has always
been due to human error.</i>

471
01:22:03.668 --> 01:22:05.378
Listen, Hal...

472
01:22:05.587 --> 01:22:07.881
...there's never been
any instance at all...

473
01:22:08.131 --> 01:22:11.343
...of a computer error
occurring in a 9000 Series, has there?

474
01:22:11.593 --> 01:22:13.178
<i>None whatsoever, Frank.</i>

475
01:22:13.386 --> 01:22:17.099
<i>The 9000 Series has
a perfect operational record.</i>

476
01:22:17.349 --> 01:22:21.645
POOLE: I know the wonderful
achievements of the 9000 Series, but....

477
01:22:22.854 --> 01:22:27.901
Are you certain there's never been even
the most insignificant computer error?

478
01:22:28.151 --> 01:22:30.112
<i>None whatsoever, Frank.</i>

479
01:22:30.487 --> 01:22:34.157
<i>Quite honestly, I wouldn't
worry myself about that.</i>

480
01:22:38.620 --> 01:22:40.831
Well, I'm sure you're right, Hal.

481
01:22:42.290 --> 01:22:44.793
Fine. Thanks very much.

482
01:22:47.337 --> 01:22:50.340
I'm having trouble
with my transmitter in C-pod.

483
01:22:50.590 --> 01:22:53.176
Would you come down
and take a look at it with me?

484
01:22:53.385 --> 01:22:54.511
See you later, Hal.

485
